Comprehensive AI-Driven Guide for Transforming Policy Recommendations in Colombian Municipalities: Integrating Value Chain Methodology, Policy Capacity Framework, and Howlett's Policy Instruments
Colombian municipal development plans face a dual crisis: the "rhetoric-reality gap" identified by CEPAL where aspirational language fails to generate executable action, and fundamental capacity deficits that prevent even well-designed policies from reaching implementation. This integrated guide synthesizes Colombia's value chain methodology (Cadena de Valor), Wu, Ramesh, and Howlett's policy capacity framework, and Howlett's comprehensive policy instruments taxonomy to create a systematic transformation pipeline—converting FARFAN diagnostic data (300 questions across 10 policy areas and 6 dimensions) into contextual, capacity-calibrated, instrument-specific recommendations that municipalities can actually execute.
The transformation challenge operates at three interdependent levels: structural (aligning with Colombian legal frameworks and planning cycles), analytical (diagnosing capacity gaps across nine dimensions), and operational (selecting appropriate policy instruments matched to institutional capabilities). Raymond Carver's minimalist principle—"No iron can pierce the heart with such force as a period put just at the right place"—provides the stylistic anchor for converting bureaucratic prose into actionable guidance.

Part I: Constitutional Architecture and Value Chain Integration
The Legal Framework That Shapes Municipal Action Space
Colombian municipalities operate within precise constitutional boundaries that determine what they can legally accomplish. Article 311 establishes municipalities as the "fundamental entity" of political-administrative organization, while Article 339 mandates that territorial development plans contain both a strategic component (diagnosis, objectives, strategies) and an investment plan (resource allocation). These aren't guidelines—they constitute binding legal architecture.
Ley 152 de 1994 (Organic Law of the Development Plan) establishes the operational timeline. Newly elected mayors have exactly four months to formulate their PDM:
MonthRequired ActivityImplications for RecommendationsJanuaryTeam formation, citizen consultationsRecommendations must be comprehensible to non-technical stakeholdersFebruaryDiagnosis completion, strategic draftFARFAN diagnostic data must be synthesized into findingsMarch 1Submit draft to Territorial Planning CouncilRecommendations need technical defensibilityMarch 31Council delivers recommendationsAnticipate revision cycles in timeline specificationsAprilAdjustments, financial harmonizationBudget sources must align with SGP structureMay 2-30Municipal Council approvalPolitical feasibility becomes critical
Ley 1551 de 2012 established the category system (Special, 1-6) based on population, fiscal capacity, and economic importance. This classification creates differential obligations and capabilities:
CategoryPopulationBudget CharacteristicsPlanning RequirementsRecommendation ImplicationsSpecial>500,000High own-source revenueComprehensive POT, full departmental structuresComplex integrated programs possible1100,001-500,000Mixed revenue streamsFull POT, professional planning officesPhased sophisticated interventions250,001-100,000Moderate own-sourceFull POT, some professional capacityMedium complexity with external technical assistance330,001-50,000SGP-dependent with some flexibilityFull POT or simplifiedPrioritize capacity building embedded in interventions420,001-30,000Highly SGP-dependentEsquema Básico possibleSequential interventions, shared services emphasis5-6<20,000Almost entirely SGPEsquema BásicoQuick wins, aggregated approaches, external TA mandatory
The Sistema General de Participaciones (SGP) channels national transfers with strict sectoral allocations:

58.5% to education (cannot be reallocated)
24.5% to health (cannot be reallocated)
11.6% to general purposes (42% discretionary for Categories 4-6)
5.4% to water and sanitation

Critical insight: The 42% discretionary component of general-purpose SGP allocation represents the primary resource pool for new policy interventions in smaller municipalities. Recommendations must explicitly reference this financing mechanism or identify co-financing arrangements.
Mapping FARFAN Policy Areas to Legal Obligations
The 10 FARFAN policy areas correspond to specific mandatory PDM components:
FARFAN Policy AreaLegal ObligationPDM Section RequiredVerification EntityGender EqualityLey 1257/2008Dedicated chapter on violence against women preventionConsejería Presidencial para la Equidad de la MujerVictims' RightsLey 1448/2011Specific chapter, coordination with national reparations programUnidad para las VíctimasChildren/YouthCódigo de Infancia Art. 204Diagnostic and strategic sectionsICBF regionalEnvironmental ManagementMultiple environmental lawsArticulation with POT/PBOT/EOTCAR (Regional Autonomous Corporation)Human Rights DefendersDecree 1066/2015Policy design requirementsMinistry of InteriorEconomic DevelopmentMunicipal competenceInvestment plan consistencyDepartmental Planning OfficeInfrastructure/MobilityMunicipal competencePOT alignmentMinistry of TransportationEducationLey 715/2001SGP education allocation useMinistry of EducationHealthLey 715/2001SGP health allocation useMinistry of HealthInstitutional CapacityLey 1474/2011 (Estatuto Anticorrupción)Transparency and anti-corruption measuresProcuraduría General
Operationalization implication: Every recommendation must explicitly reference the legal framework it operationalizes. Generic recommendations that ignore legal mandates fail the "implementability" test regardless of analytical quality.
The Value Chain as Structuring Logic for Policy Recommendations
Colombia's Dirección de Inversiones y Finanzas Públicas established the value chain methodology to improve investment project quality. The core structure:
INSUMOS → ACTIVIDADES → PRODUCTOS → OBJETIVOS ESPECÍFICOS → OBJETIVO GENERAL → RESULTADOS → IMPACTOS
For FARFAN transformation, the relevant segments are:
Objetivo General ← Objetivos Específicos ← Productos ← Actividades
This creates a critical translation requirement: FARFAN diagnostic findings must flow backwards through the chain:

Diagnostic finding (problem identification from 300-question survey)
Objetivo General (desired situation that solves the problem)
Objetivos Específicos (measurable means to achieve general objective)
Productos (goods/services that materialize specific objectives)
Actividades (actions that generate products through resource transformation)

Objective Formulation Rules (From Value Chain Guide)
Objetivo General Structure:
[VERBO INFINITIVO] + [OBJETO] + [ELEMENTOS DESCRIPTIVOS]
Example: "Disminuir los riesgos de accidentalidad vial en zonas escolares del casco urbano"

Verbo: Disminuir
Objeto: riesgos de accidentalidad vial
Descriptivos: zonas escolares del casco urbano

Common errors to avoid:

Including solution mechanisms ("mediante la construcción de...")
Including effects/impacts ("para mejorar la calidad de vida")
Describing partial actions ("adquirir equipos")
Excessive breadth ("garantizar el acceso a la educación básica y media")
Including meta targets ("beneficiar el 94% de los estudiantes")

Objetivos Específicos must:

Result from converting problem causes into desired states
Be measurable/quantifiable through their products
Complement each other to achieve the general objective
Avoid operational-level verbs (contratar, instalar)

Product Specification Rules
Producto Structure:
[BIEN O SERVICIO] + [COMPLEMENTO]
Never include condition in product name (elaborado, implementado, entregado)—condition appears in the indicator.
Examples:

✓ "Vía primaria pavimentada" (Unidad: kilómetros)
✓ "Servicio de asistencia técnica en prácticas agrícolas sostenibles" (Unidad: número de familias atendidas)
✗ "Vía construida" (condition word)
✗ "Desplazados" (not a product—who receives a product)

Verification criteria:

At least one product per specific objective
Product results from a production process (multiple activities)
Product has coherent, quantifiable unit of measure
Product has specified meta (target)

Activity Identification Rules
Activities must:

Describe value-adding transformation actions (not input acquisition)
Use specific action verbs (not fortalecer, garantizar, implementar)
Represent primary actions (not excessive disaggregation into sub-tasks)
Directly contribute to product generation

Minimum 2 activities per product (if only one activity generates a product, it's likely misidentified as a product itself)
Example for "Vía primaria construida":

Realizar estudios de diseño y trazado
Preparar y nivelar el terreno
Construir sub-base, base y capa de rodadura
Realizar señalización y demarcación


Part II: Policy Capacity Framework—The Nine-Dimensional Diagnostic
Wu, Ramesh, and Howlett's framework defines policy capacity as "the set of skills and resources—competences and capabilities—necessary to perform policy functions." This creates a 3×3 matrix generating nine distinct capacity types:
The Capacity Matrix
Analytical SkillsOperational SkillsPolitical SkillsIndividual LevelIndividual analytical capacityIndividual operational capacityIndividual political capacityOrganizational LevelOrganizational analytical capacityOrganizational operational capacityOrganizational political capacitySystemic LevelSystemic analytical capacitySystemic operational capacitySystemic political capacity
Each capacity type answers different questions about what municipalities can accomplish:
Analytical Capacities
Individual Analytical Capacity: Do municipal officials have the ability to access and apply technical/scientific knowledge and analytical techniques?

Can planning office staff interpret FARFAN diagnostic data?
Do they understand basic statistics (means, distributions, significance)?
Can they access and evaluate evidence from external sources?

Organizational Analytical Capacity: Does the municipality have information systems, evaluation processes, and organizational commitment to evidence-based policy?

Does the municipality maintain updated sociodemographic databases?
Are there established M&E (monitoring and evaluation) procedures?
Is there dedicated budget for data collection and analysis?

Systemic Analytical Capacity: What is the general state of scientific, statistical, and educational facilities in the region that municipal policy-makers can access?

Proximity to universities or research centers
Quality of departmental statistical offices (DANE presence)
Regional technical assistance networks (DNP, international cooperation)

Diagnostic questions for FARFAN integration:

If analytical capacity is low: Recommendations must include external technical assistance as an embedded component
If analytical capacity is medium: Recommendations can include capacity building elements
If analytical capacity is high: Recommendations can involve innovation and piloting

Operational Capacities
Individual Operational Capacity: Can municipal managers and staff perform key managerial functions (budgeting, procurement, HR management)?

Do they understand public procurement regulations (Colombia Compra Eficiente)?
Can they execute multi-year budget projections?
Do they know how to manage inter-institutional agreements?

Organizational Operational Capacity: Does the internal organization support effective policy execution?

Are there clear delegation structures and decision-making protocols?
Do information systems enable coordination across secretariats?
Is there continuity despite political transitions?

Systemic Operational Capacity: How well can the municipality coordinate with other governmental and non-governmental actors?

Quality of relationships with departmental government
Access to national programs (Ministry programs, ICBF, etc.)
Presence of NGOs, international cooperation, private sector allies

Diagnostic questions for FARFAN integration:

If operational capacity is low: Recommendations must emphasize shared services, aggregated approaches, and turnkey solutions
If operational capacity is medium: Recommendations can involve phased implementation with checkpoints
If operational capacity is high: Recommendations can include complex multi-stakeholder coordination

Political Capacities
Individual Political Capacity: Do policy actors have political knowledge, acumen, and understanding of stakeholder interests?

Does the planning secretary understand council dynamics?
Can they identify key community leaders and their positions?
Do they understand the mayor's political commitments and constraints?

Organizational Political Capacity: Can the municipality develop learning relationships with governance partners and the public?

Are there functional participation mechanisms (JAC, youth councils, women's councils)?
Does the administration communicate effectively with citizens?
Is there trust between municipal government and communities?

Systemic Political Capacity: What is the level of legitimacy, trust, and support the municipality enjoys in political, social, economic, and security spheres?

Electoral stability vs. volatility
Levels of armed actor presence
Social capital indicators (trust, associativity)
Fiscal legitimacy (tax compliance rates)

Diagnostic questions for FARFAN integration:

If political capacity is low: Recommendations must emphasize quick wins, visible results, and constituency building
If political capacity is medium: Recommendations can include participatory design elements
If political capacity is high: Recommendations can involve contentious reforms and long-term investments

Nested Model of Capacities and Capacity Gaps
The Wu-Ramesh-Howlett framework emphasizes capacities are nested: systemic resources shape organizational capabilities, which in turn affect individual performance. Policy failures often result from imbalanced attention to these nine components.
Critical insight for FARFAN transformation: A municipality might have high individual analytical capacity (competent planning staff) but low organizational analytical capacity (no data systems), resulting in frustrated professionals unable to perform. Recommendations must address the binding constraint in the capacity chain.
Capacity gap diagnostic tool (to be applied to each municipality before generating recommendations):
Capacity TypeEvidence SourceAssessment (Low/Medium/High)Binding Constraint?Individual AnalyticalStaff CVs, training recordsOrganizational AnalyticalM&E system existence, database qualitySystemic AnalyticalRegional institutional presenceIndividual OperationalProcurement success rate, execution efficiencyOrganizational OperationalOrganizational chart clarity, SOP existenceSystemic OperationalInter-institutional agreement count/qualityIndividual PoliticalPolitical acumen assessmentOrganizational PoliticalCitizen participation rates, complaint responseSystemic PoliticalElectoral data, social capital indicators
The binding constraint is the capacity dimension that, if improved, would unlock the greatest performance gain. Recommendations should directly address binding constraints rather than optimizing already-adequate capacities.

Part III: Howlett's Policy Instruments—Matching Tools to Problems and Capacities
Michael Howlett's taxonomy provides the critical bridge between diagnosis and action: different policy problems require different policy tools, and different tools demand different implementation capacities. The Colombian context adds legal constraints: municipalities have differentiated competencies over various policy instruments.
The NATO Classification: Four Instrument Categories
Howlett builds on Hood's nodality-authority-treasure-organization (NATO) typology but adapts it for substantive policy design:
Resource BaseGoverning InstrumentDefinitionColombian Municipal ExamplesInformation (Nodality)Information-based instrumentsUsing government's position in information networks to achieve policy goalsPublic awareness campaigns, transparency portals, educational materialsAuthorityAuthority-based instrumentsUsing legal powers to command or forbidLocal regulations (Acuerdos), land use restrictions (POT), licensing requirementsTreasure (Financial)Treasure-based instrumentsUsing government's financial resources to incentivize or enableSubsidies, grants, tax exemptions (predial, ICA), cash transfersOrganizationOrganization-based instrumentsUsing government's capacity to directly provide goods/servicesMunicipal health posts, sports facilities, public schools, road maintenance
Critical Colombian distinction: The category system limits which instruments municipalities can deploy:

Category 5-6 municipalities have minimal regulatory authority (most regulations require departmental approval)
All categories have limited fiscal instruments (cannot create new taxes, only adjust rates within national parameters)
SGP sectoral earmarks restrict treasure instruments to specific domains
Organization instruments require operational capacity and recurrent budgets

Substantive vs. Procedural Instruments
Howlett distinguishes between:
Substantive Instruments: Tools that directly affect the production, distribution, or consumption of goods and services in society

Public enterprises, subsidies, regulations, information campaigns

Procedural Instruments: Tools that structure policy processes themselves

Advisory committees, public hearings, consultation mechanisms, inter-institutional committees

Colombian application: Ley 1757 de 2015 (participatory mechanisms) mandates certain procedural instruments (e.g., Consejos Territoriales de Planeación), while substantive instruments remain at municipal discretion within legal bounds.
The Howlett Instrument Taxonomy (Adapted for Colombian Municipalities)
Information-Based Instruments
InstrumentDescriptionCapacity RequirementsColombian Legal FrameworkExample ApplicationPublic Information CampaignsGovernment disseminates information to change behaviorMedium organizational capacity, low political capitalLey 1712/2014 (Transparency)Gender violence prevention awareness campaign targeting rural communitiesExhortationOfficial recommendations or guidelines without legal forceLow capacity across dimensionsMunicipal authority under general police powersMayor's office exhorts businesses to hire youth through public lettersTraining and EducationGovernment provides skill-building opportunitiesMedium organizational capacity, requires partnershipsMunicipal education competence (non-certified municipalities)Training workshops for community mothers on child nutritionLabeling/CertificationGovernment creates information systems that classify actors/productsHigh organizational analytical capacityMunicipal sanitary authorityRestaurant hygiene rating system with public display requirement
FARFAN integration principle: Information instruments work best when systemic and organizational analytical capacity is adequate but political/operational capacity is limited. They're "soft" interventions requiring minimal enforcement.
Authority-Based Instruments
InstrumentDescriptionCapacity RequirementsColombian Legal FrameworkExample ApplicationRegulation (Command & Control)Legal rules requiring/prohibiting specific behaviorsHigh organizational operational + political capacity (enforcement demands)Municipal Councils issue Acuerdos under Ley 136/1994Acuerdo Municipal requiring construction waste management plans for all projectsSelf-RegulationGovernment mandates industry/sector creates own rulesMedium capacity, requires monitoringFramework law allowing delegationMunicipal ordinance requiring taxi drivers' association to establish service quality standardsLicensing/PermitsGovernment grants permission to engage in activitiesMedium-high organizational operational capacityVarious sectoral laws delegate permittingLiquor sales permits, small-scale mining permits (where applicable)StandardsGovernment sets performance/quality requirementsHigh analytical capacity (to set appropriate standards)NTC standards adoption at local levelBuilding code enforcement for public accessibility
Colombian constraint: Municipal regulatory authority is limited to matters not reserved to national/departmental law. Categories 5-6 often lack enforcement capacity even for valid regulations.
FARFAC integration principle: Authority instruments require high organizational operational capacity and medium-high political capacity. Avoid in low-capacity contexts unless enforcement mechanisms are specified.
Treasure-Based Instruments
InstrumentDescriptionCapacity RequirementsColombian Legal FrameworkExample ApplicationSubsidies/GrantsGovernment provides direct financial supportMedium operational capacity (targeting, disbursement)SGP allocation rules, municipal budget autonomy within limitsSubsidies for low-income families to connect to aqueduct system (co-financed with SGP water allocation)Tax ExpendituresGovernment foregoes revenue to incentivize behaviorLow-medium capacity, but foregone revenue must be sustainableLey 44/1990 allows municipal tax adjustments within parametersPredial (property tax) exemptions for properties with sustainable water systemsVouchersGovernment provides purchasing power for specific servicesMedium-high operational capacity (voucher management systems)Requires enabling Acuerdo MunicipalChildcare vouchers for working mothers using registered community mothersUser ChargesGovernment charges fees for servicesLow-medium capacity, but requires service deliveryMunicipal services pricing authorityDifferential sports facility rental rates (subsidized for youth, market rate for commercial)Procurement PreferencesGovernment uses purchasing power to favor certain suppliersMedium capacity, must comply with procurement lawLey 1150/2007 allows preferences within limitsPreferential points in municipal procurement for women-owned businesses
Colombian constraint: Municipal fiscal capacity is severely constrained. Own-source revenues are limited (predial, ICA, sobretasa a la gasolina), and SGP has strict sectoral allocations. Treasure instruments primarily draw from the 42% discretionary component of SGP general-purpose allocation (Categories 4-6) or require departmental/national co-financing.
FARFAN integration principle: Treasure instruments can work across capacity levels if financing source is identified. The challenge isn't implementation capacity but fiscal sustainability.
Organization-Based Instruments
InstrumentDescriptionCapacity RequirementsColombian Legal FrameworkExample ApplicationDirect ProvisionGovernment directly produces/delivers goods and servicesHigh organizational operational capacity, recurrent budgetMunicipal service competencies (water, local roads, health, education per Ley 715)Municipal government operates three mobile health units serving dispersed rural communitiesPublic EnterpriseGovernment creates entity to deliver servicesVery high capacity across dimensionsRequires municipal council approval, complex governanceMunicipal public enterprise for solid waste collectionGovernment ReorganizationRestructuring administrative unitsHigh political capacity, medium operationalMunicipal administrative autonomyCreating a dedicated Gender Equality Office within mayor's officeCo-productionGovernment and citizens jointly deliver servicesMedium capacity, high political-organizational capacityCommunity action boards (JAC) legal frameworkCommunity-municipal co-management of neighborhood parksAdvisory CommitteesProcedural: Structured stakeholder inputLow-medium capacityLey 1757/2015 participatory mechanismsMunicipal Council for Women's Rights (advisory to mayor)
Colombian constraint: Organization instruments require sustained operational capacity and recurrent budget. Category 5-6 municipalities often lack personnel for new organizational structures. Shared services across municipalities or delegation to departmental entities may be necessary.
FARFAN integration principle: Organization instruments should only be recommended when organizational operational capacity is medium-high OR when the recommendation explicitly includes external implementation support (e.g., national program establishes and initially staffs the service).
Instrument Mixes and Sequencing
Critical insight from Howlett: Policy problems rarely yield to single instruments. Effective policy design requires instrument mixes calibrated to:

Policy context (legal, fiscal, institutional constraints)
Problem characteristics (complexity, controversy, urgency)
Available capacity (across nine dimensions)

Instrument sequencing principles for Colombian municipalities:
Phase 1—Quick Wins (Months 1-6 of PDM):

Emphasize information instruments (low capacity demands, visible)
Use existing organizational instruments (redirect resources vs. create new)
Deploy procedural instruments (establish committees, consultation mechanisms)

Phase 2—Capacity Building (Months 7-18):

Introduce training/education (building individual capacity)
Pilot co-production arrangements (building organizational political capacity)
Initiate external technical assistance relationships (building analytical capacity)

Phase 3—Substantive Interventions (Months 19-48):

Implement treasure instruments (subsidies, grants) if financing secured
Enact regulations if enforcement capacity built
Launch direct provision if operational capacity adequate

Colombian example of instrument mix (Gender-Based Violence Prevention—FARFAN Gender Equality area):
Instrument TypeSpecific InstrumentImplementation TimelineCapacity RequirementLegal FrameworkInformationPublic awareness campaign on violence reporting mechanismsMonths 1-6 (ongoing)LowMunicipal communications authorityProceduralMunicipal Committee on Violence Against WomenMonth 2 (establishment)Low-mediumLey 1257/2008 requirementOrganizationCasa de la Mujer (women's resource center)Months 6-12 (planning), 13-24 (implementation)Medium-highAcuerdo Municipal + SGP general purpose allocationTreasureTransportation vouchers for women seeking legal/psychological servicesMonths 12-48MediumMunicipal budget + departmental co-financingAuthorityAcuerdo Municipal requiring police priority response to domestic violence callsMonths 18-24 (drafting/approval)Medium political capacityMunicipal Council legislative authority

Part IV: The Transformation Pipeline—From FARFAN Diagnostics to Executable Recommendations
Step 1: Data Synthesis and Problem Tree Construction
Input: FARFAN diagnostic data—300 questions across 10 policy areas and 6 dimensions, disaggregated to municipal level.
Process:

Aggregate responses within each dimension to create dimensional profiles:

Calculate percentage distributions for Likert-scale responses
Identify statistically significant gaps (>20 percentage points from desired state)
Flag open-ended responses indicating critical issues


Create composite profiles per policy area:

Map how the 6 dimensions intersect within each policy area
Identify convergent problems (same issue appearing across multiple dimensions)
Prioritize based on severity (% affected), urgency (legal mandate), feasibility (capacity to address)


Construct problem tree (adapted from value chain methodology):

   EFFECTS (consequences of the problem)
        ↑
   CENTRAL PROBLEM (negative situation requiring intervention)
        ↑
   CAUSES (why the problem exists)
Example—From FARFAN Data to Problem Tree:
FARFAN findings (Gender Equality area, hypothetical Category 5 municipality):

78% of respondents indicate lack of knowledge about gender violence reporting mechanisms
65% report no specialized services for survivors within the municipality
Municipal budget allocates 0% to gender equality programs
No municipal entity responsible for gender issues
43% of respondents report experiencing or knowing someone who experienced gender violence without formal reporting

Problem Tree:
EFFECTS:
- Normalized gender violence
- Survivors lack access to justice and reparation
- Perpetuation of discriminatory practices

CENTRAL PROBLEM:
- Women in [Municipality] lack access to violence prevention, attention, and reparation services

CAUSES:
- Insufficient awareness of rights and reporting mechanisms
- Absence of specialized care services
- No institutional structure for gender policy
- Zero budget allocation for gender programs
Step 2: Objective Formulation Using Value Chain Principles
Process:

Convert central problem to Objetivo General:

Invert the negative statement to positive desired state
Structure: [VERBO INFINITIVO] + [OBJETO] + [ELEMENTOS DESCRIPTIVOS]
Verify it solves the problem without including solution mechanisms

Example: "Garantizar el acceso de las mujeres a servicios integrales de prevención, atención y reparación de violencias de género en [Municipality]"
Convert causes to Objetivos Específicos:

Each cause becomes a specific objective
Must be measurable through products
Collectively, achieving all specific objectives must accomplish general objective

Examples:

Cause: Insufficient awareness → Objective: "Aumentar el conocimiento de las mujeres y la comunidad sobre derechos y mecanismos de denuncia"
Cause: Absence of services → Objective: "Establecer servicios especializados de atención psicológica, jurídica y social para sobrevivientes de violencia de género"
Cause: No institutional structure → Objective: "Crear capacidad institucional municipal para la formulación y seguimiento de política de género"
Cause: Zero budget → Objective: "Asignar recursos presupuestales sostenibles para programas de equidad de género"


Verification:

Are specific objectives measurable/quantifiable? (Yes—each has verifiable metrics)
If achieved complementarily, do they accomplish the general objective? (Yes—awareness + services + institutional capacity + budget = access to comprehensive services)
Do they avoid operational-level verbs? (Yes—aumentar, establecer, crear, asignar are strategic, not operational)



Step 3: Capacity Assessment and Binding Constraint Identification
Process: Apply the 9-dimensional capacity framework:
Capacity DimensionAssessment (Low/Med/High)EvidenceImplication for Instrument SelectionIndividual AnalyticalLowPlanning office has 2 staff, no advanced training in gender analysisRecommendations must include external technical assistanceOrganizational AnalyticalLowNo gender-disaggregated data collection systemsInformation instruments need external implementation supportSystemic AnalyticalMediumRegional university 40km away, departmental women's office existsCan leverage external expertise for analysisIndividual OperationalMediumStaff understand basic procurement, budget execution at 75%Can implement treasure instruments with moderate complexityOrganizational OperationalLowHigh staff turnover, no SOPs, weak inter-secretariat coordinationOrganization instruments (new offices) risky without reorganizationSystemic OperationalMediumFunctional relationship with departmental government, ICBF presentCan establish inter-institutional agreementsIndividual PoliticalLowNew administration, mayor has no prior gender policy experienceRequires political capacity building, stakeholder engagementOrganizational PoliticalLowNo existing women's participation mechanisms, low trustProcedural instruments (committees) essential as foundationSystemic PoliticalMediumModerate social capital, functional JACs, stable electoral environmentParticipatory approaches feasible if well-designed
Binding Constraint Identification:
Primary binding constraint: Organizational Political Capacity (Low)—Without trust and participation mechanisms, even well-designed services won't be accessed; women won't engage with municipal programs.
Secondary binding constraint: Organizational Analytical Capacity (Low)—Cannot design evidence-based interventions or monitor progress without data systems.
Implication: Recommendations must sequence interventions to address binding constraints first:

Phase 1: Build organizational political capacity through procedural instruments (committees, consultations)
Phase 2: Build organizational analytical capacity through information systems with external support
Phase 3: Implement substantive services (organization/treasure instruments) once foundation exists

Step 4: Instrument Selection Matched to Objectives and Capacity
Process: For each Objetivo Específico, identify the instrument mix most likely to succeed given capacity constraints.
Example—Objetivo Específico 1: "Aumentar el conocimiento de las mujeres y la comunidad sobre derechos y mecanismos de denuncia"
Candidate Instruments:
InstrumentProsConsCapacity FitPublic information campaignLow capacity demands, quick implementation, visibleLimited effectiveness without supporting servicesGood fit—can implement immediately despite low capacityTraining workshopsMore interactive, builds skills beyond awarenessRequires facilitation capacity, higher cost per person reachedModerate fit—if external facilitators usedRadio programsReaches dispersed rural populationRequires ongoing content productionModerate fit—if partnerships with community radioSchool curriculum integrationReaches youth, sustainableLong timeline, requires Education Secretariat coordinationPoor fit—requires organizational operational capacity not present
Selected Instrument Mix:

Primary: Public information campaign (information instrument)
Supporting: Training workshops for community leaders (information + procedural—builds individual political capacity)
Enabling: Municipal Committee on Violence Against Women (procedural instrument—addresses organizational political capacity deficit)

Example—Objetivo Específico 2: "Establecer servicios especializados de atención psicológica, jurídica y social para sobrevivientes de violencia de género"
Candidate Instruments:
InstrumentProsConsCapacity FitDirect municipal provision (Casa de la Mujer)Comprehensive, municipal controlVery high operational capacity demands, recurrent budget needsPoor fit—organizational operational capacity too lowAgreement with departmental women's office for service provisionLeverages existing capacity, lower municipal burdenLess municipal control, depends on departmental availabilityGood fit—addresses operational capacity gapVoucher system for private service providersFlexibility, market-basedRequires provider network that may not exist in small municipalityPoor fit—insufficient provider ecosystemCo-production with NGOContinuar7:51 p. m.Share capability, builds civil society | Requires finding willing NGO partner | Moderate fit—if partner identified |
Selected Instrument Mix:

Primary: Inter-institutional agreement with departmental women's office (organization instrument—delegation model)
Supporting: Transportation vouchers for women to access departmental services (treasure instrument—addresses geographic access barrier)
Transition: Gradual municipal capacity building toward future direct provision (organization instrument—long-term goal)

Step 5: Product and Activity Specification (Value Chain Integration)
Process: For each selected instrument, define the Productos (goods/services) and Actividades (value-adding actions) following value chain rules.
Example—Public Information Campaign (addresses Objetivo Específico 1):
Producto 1: "Campaña comunicacional sobre prevención de violencias de género y rutas de atención"

Unidad de medida: Número (1 campaign)
Meta: 1 campaign implemented reaching 80% of urban households and 60% of rural households

Actividades (minimum 2):

Diseñar mensajes y materiales comunicacionales con enfoque diferencial y pertinencia cultural
Difundir la campaña a través de emisora comunitaria, perifoneo, y material impreso distribuido en tiendas, colegios, y espacios comunitarios
Capacitar a líderes comunitarios como multiplicadores de información

Producto 2: "Comité Municipal de Prevención de Violencias contra las Mujeres conformado y funcionando"

Unidad de medida: Número (1 committee)
Meta: 1 committee with 12 members meeting monthly

Actividades:

Convocar y seleccionar miembros del comité (representantes de secretarías, JAC, organizaciones de mujeres, personería)
Elaborar y aprobar reglamento interno y plan de trabajo del comité
Realizar sesiones mensuales de seguimiento a política de género con actas públicas

Example—Inter-institutional Agreement (addresses Objetivo Específico 2):
Producto: "Convenio interadministrativo con Secretaría Departamental de la Mujer para prestación de servicios de atención a sobrevivientes de violencia de género"

Unidad de medida: Número (1 agreement)
Meta: 1 agreement enabling 40 women/year to access psychological, legal, and social services

Actividades:

Negociar términos del convenio incluyendo responsabilidades, costos compartidos, y protocolos de referencia
Tramitar y aprobar convenio en Consejo de Gobierno Municipal y estructuras departamentales correspondientes
Establecer mecanismo de referencia de casos desde Comisaría de Familia municipal a servicios departamentales
Asignar presupuesto para transporte de mujeres y apoyo económico temporal durante procesos de atención

Step 6: Resource Identification and Timeline Integration
Process: For each producto, specify:

Budget source (SGP allocation, own-source revenue, co-financing)
Amount (cost estimate)
Timeline (aligned with PDM 4-year cycle and annual budget cycles)
Responsible entity (specific municipal office or external partner)
Verification mechanism (how success will be monitored)

Example—Campaign Product Budget:
ComponentCost (COP)SourceTimelineResponsibleDesign consultancy (external)15,000,000SGP General Purpose (42% discretionary)Months 3-4 of Year 1Planning Office contracts, Women's Committee overseesMaterials production (radio spots, posters, flyers)8,000,000SGP General Purpose + own-source (ICA)Month 5 of Year 1Communications OfficeRadio airtime (6 months)6,000,000In-kind (community radio agreement)Months 6-11 of Year 1Communications OfficeCommunity leader training (3 workshops)4,500,000Co-financing with departmental women's officeMonths 6-8 of Year 1Social Development Office + Departmental entityTOTAL33,500,000MixedYear 1Cross-secretariat coordination
Verification: Monthly meeting attendance records; pre-post knowledge surveys (baseline Month 5, endline Month 12); number of inquiries to Comisaría de Familia
Example—Inter-institutional Agreement Budget:
ComponentCost (COP)SourceTimelineResponsibleMunicipal co-financing contribution (per agreement)18,000,000/yearSGP General PurposeYears 1-4 (annual)Finance Office budgets, Social Development executesTransportation vouchers (40 women × COP 200,000 avg)8,000,000/yearSGP General PurposeYears 1-4 (annual)Social Development OfficePart-time case manager (municipal side)24,000,000/yearSGP General Purpose + Own-sourceYears 2-4 (Year 1 uses existing Comisaría staff)Social Development OfficeTOTAL YEAR 126,000,000Municipal budgetYear 1InterdepartmentalTOTAL RECURRING50,000,000/yearMixedYears 2-4Institutionalized
Verification: Quarterly reports from departmental office on women served; satisfaction surveys; tracking of referral-to-service completion rates
Step 7: Narrative Operationalization—Converting Structured Data to Integrated Prose
Process: Transform the structured elements (objectives, products, activities, budgets, timelines, verification) into narrative prose that:

Embeds all critical information in natural flow (no bullet points unless explicitly requested)
Follows Lenguaje Claro principles (familiar words, concrete nouns, active verbs, short sentences)
Makes implementation steps obvious to non-technical readers
Maintains precision (numbers, dates, responsible entities all specified)

Template for Narrative Integration:
El diagnóstico FARFAN identificó [PROBLEMA CON EVIDENCIA CUANTITATIVA]. Esta situación requiere que [ENTIDAD RESPONSABLE] implemente [ACCIÓN ESPECÍFICA CON PRODUCTOS] para [OBJETIVO ESPECÍFICO], contribuyendo así a [OBJETIVO GENERAL]. 

La intervención se desarrollará mediante [INSTRUMENTO TIPO], concretamente [DESCRIPCIÓN DEL PRODUCTO]. Durante [PERÍODO ESPECÍFICO], [ACTOR] ejecutará las siguientes acciones principales: [ACTIVIDAD 1], [ACTIVIDAD 2], [ACTIVIDAD 3]. La inversión total asciende a COP [MONTO], financiada con recursos de [FUENTE PRESUPUESTAL]. 

El seguimiento se realizará mediante [MECANISMO DE VERIFICACIÓN] con reportes [PERIODICIDAD] a [ENTIDAD SUPERVISORA], buscando alcanzar la meta de [META CUANTIFICADA] para [FECHA LÍMITE].
Example—Objective 1 Narrative (replacing bullet points):
"El diagnóstico FARFAN reveló que el 78% de las mujeres encuestadas desconoce las rutas de denuncia y atención disponibles frente a violencias de género, mientras que el 43% reporta haber experimentado o conocer casos de violencia sin ninguna acción formal. Esta grave brecha de información requiere que la Alcaldía Municipal, a través de su Oficina de Comunicaciones en coordinación con la Secretaría de Desarrollo Social, diseñe e implemente una campaña comunicacional integral que aumente el conocimiento comunitario sobre derechos, mecanismos de denuncia y rutas de atención disponibles.
La campaña se ejecutará entre los meses 3 y 11 del primer año del Plan de Desarrollo Municipal, articulándose con la conformación simultánea del Comité Municipal de Prevención de Violencias contra las Mujeres. La Oficina de Comunicaciones contratará mediante el mes 3 un equipo consultor (COP 15 millones, financiados con el componente de libre destinación del SGP) para diseñar mensajes culturalmente pertinentes y materiales gráficos apropiados al contexto rural y urbano del municipio. Durante el mes 5, se producirán cuñas radiales, afiches y volantes (COP 8 millones) que se difundirán de manera intensiva entre los meses 6 y 11 a través de la emisora comunitaria (con la cual se firmará convenio de colaboración sin transferencia de recursos), perifoneo en veredas, y distribución en tiendas, colegios y salones comunales.
Paralelamente, la Secretaría de Desarrollo Social coordinará con la Secretaría Departamental de la Mujer (mediante cofinanciamiento de COP 4.5 millones) tres talleres de capacitación dirigidos a 36 líderes comunitarios—12 por taller—para que actúen como multiplicadores en sus comunidades. Estos líderes recibirán materiales de apoyo y un protocolo sencillo para orientar a mujeres que soliciten información.
El Comité Municipal de Prevención de Violencias contra las Mujeres, conformado formalmente mediante Decreto Municipal en el mes 2 y compuesto por 12 miembros (representantes de la Comisaría de Familia, Personería, Secretarías de Salud, Educación y Desarrollo Social, dos representantes de Juntas de Acción Comunal, tres representantes de organizaciones de mujeres, y un delegado de la Policía Nacional), se reunirá mensualmente para supervisar la implementación de la campaña y analizar información sobre casos reportados. Las actas de estas reuniones serán públicas y estarán disponibles en el portal web municipal.
El seguimiento se realizará mediante tres mecanismos complementarios: encuestas de conocimiento aplicadas en el mes 5 (línea base) y mes 12 (línea final) a una muestra representativa de 200 mujeres; conteo mensual de consultas recibidas en la Comisaría de Familia sobre rutas de denuncia; y registro de asistencia a los talleres para líderes. La meta es alcanzar un incremento del 50% en el conocimiento de rutas de denuncia (del 22% actual al 72%) y duplicar el número de consultas mensuales a la Comisaría (de 3 a 6 casos/mes) para diciembre del primer año. La Secretaría de Desarrollo Social presentará reportes trimestrales de estos indicadores al Comité Municipal y al Despacho del Alcalde."
Analysis of narrative:

✓ Problem with quantitative evidence (78%, 43%)
✓ Responsible entities named (Oficina de Comunicaciones, Secretaría de Desarrollo Social, Comisaría de Familia, etc.)
✓ Specific actions described (diseñar mensajes, producir materiales, difundir, capacitar líderes)
✓ Timeline integrated naturally (meses 3, 5, 6-11, 12)
✓ Budget amounts specified (COP 15M, 8M, 4.5M)
✓ Financing sources identified (SGP componente libre destinación, cofinanciamiento departamental, convenio sin transferencia)
✓ Products clearly described (campaña comunicacional, comité municipal, líderes capacitados)
✓ Verification mechanisms detailed (encuestas, conteo mensual, registro asistencia)
✓ Quantitative targets (50% incremento, duplicar consultas)
✓ Active voice, concrete nouns, familiar language (no bureaucratic abstractions)
✓ No bullet points—continuous prose flow

Step 8: AI-Driven Quality Verification and Iterative Refinement
Process: Apply automated filters and LLM evaluation to identify weaknesses before finalization.
Automated Quality Filters (flag for review):

Sentences containing hedging language ("should consider," "may want to," "could potentially," "various applicable")
Absence of named entities (no specific offices, no person roles, no institutional actors)
Absence of numbers (no dates, no budget amounts, no quantitative targets)
Passive voice constructions without clear actor
Generic qualifiers ("adequate resources," "appropriate measures," "relevant stakeholders")
Hidden verbs/nominalizations ("efectuar la implementación" vs. "implementar")

LLM Evaluation Prompt:
You are evaluating a policy recommendation for a Colombian municipality. The recommendation should be executable, calibrated to institutional capacity, and compliant with Colombian legal frameworks.

RECOMMENDATION TEXT:
[PASTE NARRATIVE]

MUNICIPALITY CONTEXT:
- Category: [5/6 etc.]
- Population: [number]
- Capacity Assessment: [summary from Step 3]

EVALUATE AGAINST THESE CRITERIA (score each 1-5, provide evidence):

1. EXECUTABILITY
   - Does it specify WHO is responsible? (Name specific municipal office/role)
   - Does it specify WHAT concrete actions? (Not vague verbs like "fortalecer")
   - Does it specify WHEN/timeline? (Specific months/years)
   - Does it specify HOW MUCH resources? (Specific budget amounts)
   - Does it identify budget SOURCE? (SGP allocation, co-financing, etc.)
   - Does it include HOW to verify success? (Specific metrics, reporting frequency)

2. CAPACITY CALIBRATION
   - Is the complexity matched to organizational operational capacity?
   - Does it address or work around analytical capacity deficits?
   - Does it build political capacity or presume it exists?
   - If capacity is low, does it include external support mechanisms?

3. LEGAL COMPLIANCE
   - Does it reference applicable legal framework (Ley, Decreto, Acuerdo)?
   - Are the instruments deployed within municipal competencies?
   - Does it align with mandatory PDM components for this policy area?

4. VALUE CHAIN COHERENCE
   - Is the Objetivo Específico clearly identified?
   - Are Productos (goods/services) specified with units of measure?
   - Are Actividades (value-adding actions) described?
   - Do Actividades → Productos → Objetivos form logical chain?

5. LANGUAGE QUALITY (Lenguaje Claro)
   - Active voice vs. passive?
   - Concrete nouns vs. abstractions?
   - Familiar words vs. bureaucratic jargon?
   - Appropriate sentence length (under 25 words avg)?

6. INSTRUMENT APPROPRIATENESS
   - Is the policy instrument (information/authority/treasure/organization) explicitly identified?
   - Is it the right instrument for the problem and capacity?
   - If multiple instruments, is the mix coherent?

7. LEVERAGE POINTS
   - Does it identify non-obvious intervention opportunities?
   - Does it address system structure vs. just parameters?
   - Does it create enabling conditions for future interventions?

PROVIDE:
- Overall score (1-5)
- Specific weaknesses with evidence from text
- Transformation recommendations if score <4
Quality Band Classification (based on LLM evaluation):
BandScoreCriteria MetActionExcelente4.5-5.0All dimensions strong, identifies leverage points, fully executableApprove for publicationBueno3.5-4.4Solid executability, minor gaps in calibration or languageMinor refinementsAceptable2.5-3.4Core elements present but generic or capacity mismatchAI transformation roundCrítico1.5-2.4Major feasibility issues, weak problem linkageReject and regenerate with revised inputsCrisis<1.5Fundamental diagnostic gaps, unviableFlag for manual expert intervention
Iterative Refinement Protocol:

If Excelente/Bueno: Human editor makes minor stylistic adjustments
If Aceptable: Apply transformation prompt (below) and re-evaluate
If Crítico: Return to Step 4 (instrument selection) with refined capacity assessment
If Crisis: Escalate to policy expert for manual diagnosis review

Transformation Prompt (for Aceptable-band recommendations):
You are a Colombian policy editor transforming a recommendation from acceptable to excellent quality.

ORIGINAL RECOMMENDATION:
[PASTE TEXT]

EVALUATION FEEDBACK:
[PASTE LLM EVAL RESULTS]

MUNICIPALITY CONTEXT:
Category [X], Population [Y], Capacity profile [summary]

TRANSFORM THE RECOMMENDATION TO:

1. INCREASE SPECIFICITY
   - Replace generic terms with exact institutional actors (not "autoridades competentes" but "Secretaría de [X]")
   - Replace vague verbs with precise actions (not "fortalecer" but "contratar 2 profesionales en", "establecer sistema de", etc.)
   - Add missing numbers (dates, amounts, quantities)

2. IMPROVE CAPACITY CALIBRATION
   - If organizational capacity is LOW: Add external technical assistance explicitly, specify which entity provides it
   - If analytical capacity is LOW: Include data collection/M&E as an embedded activity with external support
   - If political capacity is LOW: Add consultation/participation mechanisms as enabling activities

3. STRENGTHEN LEGAL GROUNDING
   - Reference specific legal framework (Ley X de YEAR, Decreto Y, Acuerdo Municipal)
   - Verify instruments are within municipal competency for this category

4. REFINE BUDGET SPECIFICATION
   - If SGP allocation mentioned generically, specify which component (education 58.5%, health 24.5%, general purpose 11.6% with 42% discretionary for cat. 4-6, water 5.4%)
   - If co-financing mentioned, specify partner entity and percentage split
   - If amounts missing, provide reasonable estimates based on Colombian costs

5. ENHANCE VERIFICATION
   - Replace "se hará seguimiento" with specific mechanism (monthly reports to X office, quarterly verification visits, baseline/endline surveys)
   - Add reporting frequency and responsible entity

6. APPLY LENGUAJE CLARO
   - Convert passive to active voice
   - Replace nominalizations (carry out implementation → implement)
   - Shorten sentences over 25 words
   - Use concrete nouns (not "recursos" but "3 computadores, 2 profesionales, sistema de software X")

7. MAINTAIN NARRATIVE FLOW
   - Do NOT convert to bullet points unless explicitly requested
   - Integrate all elements (problem→action→timeline→budget→verification) in continuous prose
   - Use transition phrases naturally

OUTPUT:
Rewritten recommendation in narrative prose following Lenguaje Claro principles, maintaining natural flow from diagnosis to action to verification.

Part V: Leverage Points and Non-Obvious Interventions
Donella Meadows' 12 leverage points framework reveals that the most powerful interventions operate at system structure levels rather than parameter adjustments. For FARFAN transformation, this means identifying where small, strategic interventions create cascading effects across policy areas.
The Leverage Point Hierarchy (Adapted for Municipal Policy)
Leverage Point LevelIntervention TypeColombian Municipal ExampleFARFAN Integration12. Parameters (weakest)Adjusting quantities within existing structuresIncreasing budget allocation to existing programMost FARFAN recommendations risk stopping here11. BuffersChanging stock sizes relative to flowsBuilding reserve funds, expanding service capacityFeasible for treasure instruments with fiscal space10. Stock-and-flow structuresPhysical system redesignReorganizing municipal administrative structureRequires high organizational operational capacity9. DelaysChanging response timesStreamlining permit processes, accelerating procurementMedium capacity demand, high citizen impact8. Negative feedback loopsStrengthening stabilizing mechanismsCreating citizen oversight committees that monitor service qualityBuilds political capacity, enables other interventions7. Positive feedback loopsControlling reinforcing mechanismsBreaking cycles of distrust through transparencyAddresses systemic political capacity6. Information flows (strong)Creating new data visibilityGender-disaggregated reporting requirements for all municipal programsHigh-leverage, medium-capacity demand5. System rulesChanging incentives/punishmentsMunicipal regulations requiring gender impact assessmentsRequires political capacity, enables analytical capacity4. Self-organizationFostering system evolution capacitySupporting women's organizations to become policy co-designersBuilds systemic political capacity organically3. GoalsChanging optimization targetsShifting from "service provision" to "outcome achievement" paradigmsRequires political leadership, reshapes all instruments2. ParadigmsChanging fundamental assumptionsFrom paternalistic service delivery to rights-based approachesLong-term, requires sustained political will1. Transcending paradigms (strongest)Flexibility to change paradigmsInstitutional learning systems that continuously question assumptionsBeyond typical PDM scope
Identifying Leverage Points in FARFAN Data
Process:

Map interconnections across 10 policy areas:

Where do findings from Gender Equality intersect with Children/Youth, Victims' Rights, Economic Development?
Example: Gender violence affects women's economic participation (economic development), children's wellbeing (children/youth), and overlaps with armed conflict impacts (victims' rights)


Identify convergent problems:

If multiple policy areas show similar gaps (e.g., lack of data systems), addressing once creates multi-area benefits
Example: Implementing a gender-disaggregated municipal data system (Point 6—information flows) simultaneously improves:

Gender equality policy design
Children/youth program targeting (single mothers, adolescent girls)
Economic development initiatives (women entrepreneurs tracking)
Victims' reparations (gender-based violence in armed conflict)




Seek "acupuncture points":

Where are existing structures already in flux? (New administration, recent legal requirement, external funding opportunity)
Where would intervention require minimal resources but maximum disruption of negative patterns?
Example: Municipal procurement represents ~40% of municipal budget; adding gender criteria to procurement (Point 5—rules) leverages existing resource flows without new budget


Target enabling conditions rather than direct problems:

Instead of "provide more services" (Point 12—parameter), ask "what prevents services from emerging organically?"
Example: Instead of municipal government directly providing childcare (high organizational operational capacity demand), change rules to enable community mothers to formalize micro-enterprises (Point 5—rules, lower capacity demand)



Cross-Cutting Leverage Point Example: Gender-Disaggregated Municipal Data System
FARFAN diagnostic reveals:

Gender Equality: No data on women's access to municipal services
Economic Development: No tracking of women entrepreneurs in municipal procurement or business licensing
Children/Youth: No data on adolescent girls' school dropout rates vs. boys
Health: No gender-disaggregated epidemiological data
Victims' Rights: No tracking of gender-based violence in conflict-affected populations

Conventional low-leverage response (Point 12—Parameters):

Increase budget for each area's data collection independently
Result: Fragmented efforts, high cost, sustainability issues

High-leverage response (Point 6—Information Flows):

Recommendation: "Establecer sistema transversal de desagregación por sexo en todas las bases de datos municipales, incluyendo registro de beneficiarios de programas, sistemas de salud, matrículas escolares, licencias comerciales, y participación en contratación pública"

Why this is high-leverage:

One structural intervention, multiple policy area benefits
Creates visibility that changes behavior: Once gender gaps are visible in procurement data, procurement officers face pressure to address disparities
Enables evidence-based policy across all sectors simultaneously
Low implementation complexity (Point 6 interventions require analytical capacity, but external technical assistance can provide it)
Sustainability: Once information flows established, they persist with minimal maintenance
Cascading effects: Other actors (departmental government, NGOs, researchers) can use data, creating accountability pressure

Instrument specification:

Primary instrument: Authority-based (Acuerdo Municipal requiring gender disaggregation in all municipal data systems)
Supporting instruments:

Organization: Technical assistance agreement with DANE or DNP for system design
Treasure: Budget allocation for software adaptation/training (COP 40M one-time, COP 8M/year maintenance)
Information: Public dashboard displaying gender-disaggregated indicators



Capacity calibration:

Requires: Medium organizational analytical capacity (which Category 5-6 municipalities lack)
Mitigation: External technical assistance from DANE or national gender machinery designs system; municipality only maintains data entry
Builds: Organizational analytical capacity over time as staff learn to use data

Value chain integration:

Objetivo General: Fundamentar las políticas municipales en evidencia desagregada por sexo que visibilice brechas de género
Objetivo Específico: Generar información sistemática sobre acceso diferenciado de mujeres y hombres a servicios y oportunidades municipales
Producto: Sistema de información municipal con módulo de desagregación por sexo implementado (Unidad: 1 sistema)
Actividades:

Realizar diagnóstico técnico de bases de datos existentes con apoyo de DANE regional
Adaptar software de gestión para incluir campos obligatorios de sexo/género
Capacitar a funcionarios responsables de captura de datos en cada secretaría
Diseñar y publicar panel de indicadores desagregados en portal web municipal




